elieve this. First TripAdvisor doesn’t recognise Welsh, now the Guardian. It’s enough to drive you <em>hollol wyllt</em>.</p> <p><strong>TripAdvisor doesn’t recognise Welsh?</strong> Not even slightly. A Welsh tour guide is kicking off because <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/travel/travel_news/article-3325050/TripAdvisor-sparks-outrage-refusing-run-review-s-written-WELSH.html#ixzz3s1bR5XFs\">TripAdvisor rejected his Welsh review</a>, on the basis that it violated the site’s language policy.</p> <p><strong>Really? What was he reviewing?</strong> The <a href=\"http://www.llyn-maritime-museum.co.uk/\">Llyn Maritime Museum</a>, a small attraction in a church in Nefyn.</p> <p><strong>And what did he think of it?</strong> We’ll never know. TripAdvisor rejected his review. However, <a href=\"http://www.tripadvisor.co.uk/Attractions-g1097184-Activities-Nefyn_Gwynedd_North_Wales_Wales.html\">based on its English reviews</a>, the museum is the best attraction in Nefyn, ahead of a 19th-century watch tower and <a href=\"http://www.tripadvisor.co.uk/Attractions-g1097184-Activities-Nefyn_Gwynedd_North_Wales_Wales.htm\">two transit vans</a> in a car park.</p> <p><strong>Ooh, I like transit vans.</strong> Listen, that’s not important. What’s important is that TripAdvisor is unwittingly <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/aug/12/welsh-language-extinction-use\">marginalising a language spoken by more than half a million people</a>.</p> <p><strong>Is the tour guide annoyed?</strong> He is. Emrys Llewelyn called it an insult, <a href=\"http://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/tripadvisor-refuses-publish-welsh-language-10456813\">saying</a>: “Welsh is a major language but TripAdvisor do not seem to think so. It’s difficult to keep a temper about something like this … TripAdvisor are making fools of themselves.”</p> <p><strong>Did he say all that in English?</strong> Well, yes, but that’s not the point. There are communities that would find Welsh-language reviews incredibly useful.</p> <p><strong>Communities who enjoy reading what someone with too much time on his hands thinks about a canoe in a church?</strong> Why not?</p> <p><strong>Then why don’t they just look at the museum’s website? That’s </strong><a href=\"http://www.llyn-maritime-museum.co.uk/\"><strong>in Welsh</strong></a><strong>.</strong> You’re not helping.</p> <p><strong>How has TripAdvisor countered this criticism?</strong> It says that, currently, it doesn’t have the capacity for Welsh-language moderation and fraud detection, so it’s better to reject all Welsh reviews outright than compromise the integrity of its site.</p> <p><strong>Still, at least this is good publicity for the museum.</strong> I know. It really looks quite nice.</p> <p><strong>Do say:</strong> “A global organisation such as TripAdvisor should be better at facilitating the needs of its own user base.”</p> <p><strong>Don’t say:</strong> “<em>Does neb yn siarad Cymraeg beth bynnag</em>.”</p>","internalOctopusCode":"11000383","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-23T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2410940","internalRevision":"85","internalContentCode":"458414927","publication":"The Guardian","trailText":"The travel website bans posts that ‘violate its language policy’ and that includes anything written in Welsh - even though more than half a million people speak it","allowUgc":"false","headline":"What's TripAdvisor's problem with Welsh reviews?","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","commentable":"true","firstPublicationDate":"2015-11-22T17:00:04Z","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/87a063a195326093d52139e4c0771f6573da9e9c/0_503_3622_2173/140.jpg","isPremoderated":"false","internalComposerCode":"564f3551e4b0875ba8d6dbf4","newspaperPageNumber":"3","commentCloseDate":"2015-11-25T17:00:04Z","standfirst":"<p>The travel website bans posts that ‘violate its language policy’ and that includes anything written in Welsh – even though more than h