_2191/1000.jpg\" alt=\"‘Do you promise to take half your in-laws’ dosh after your acrimonious divorce?’ ‘I do.’\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">‘Do you promise to take half your in-laws’ dosh after your acrimonious divorce?’ ‘I do.’</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: James Henry/Getty Images</span> </figcaption> </figure>","liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<p><strong>Name:</strong> Prenuptial agreement.</p> <p><strong>Also known as:</strong> A prenup.</p> <p><strong>Appearance:</strong> A piece of paper with writing on it.</p> <p><strong>You mean like this one?</strong> Yes. Unless you’re one of those people who reads this on the internet without paying.</p> <p><strong>Surely no one could be so dishonest?</strong> I’m afraid some people could, and you can never be sure which ones. That’s why prenups exist, in fact.</p> <p><strong>What are they?</strong> You know when you are in love and get married to someone?</p> <p><strong>Yeah.</strong> And you know when it all sours and you realise that they’re just lying, cheating filth and you end up living in a car park writing poems about how ugly their dog is?</p> <p><strong>Yeah.</strong> Well, prenups exist to manage that situation.</p> <p><strong>Do they poison my ex-partner? </strong>Not exactly. They specify in advance how the possessions of an engaged couple should be divided in the event of their divorce.</p> <p><strong>They get nothing, not even clothes or food. </strong>That would be an extreme example. Anyway, <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/property/article-3315817/Bank-Mum-Dad-forces-grown-children-sign-pre-nups-don-t-lose-cash-relationship-breaks-down.html\" title=\"\">a newspaper has reported that the Law Society is getting an increasing number of inquiries about prenups</a>.</p> <p><strong>How come?</strong> I suppose they think that people want to read about it.</p> <p><strong>No, I mean how come more people want prenups?</strong> Apparently it’s being driven by the in-laws.</p> <p><strong>How so? </strong>Marrying couples often want to buy a house together but, in order to do so, they may well need a parent’s help to put down a deposit, probably amounting to tens of thousands of pounds. That parent wants to make sure their son- or daughter-in-law won’t walk off with half the money later, so they suggest that the couple sign a prenup specifying that their child would keep it all.</p> <p><strong>And that settles it?</strong> Heavens, no. British prenups aren’t legally binding or anything. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2014/feb/27/pre-numpial-agreements-legally-binding-divorce-law-commission\" title=\"\">The Law Commission has recommended that they should become so</a>, as long as the couple and their children are properly looked after, but for now they just provide something for divorce courts to think about. There isn’t really an alternative.</p> <p><strong>Couldn’t you just prove that you really are “gaining a son/daughter” by accepting that they have the same rights to your money? </strong>Don’t be ridiculous.</p> <p><strong>Do say: </strong>“Do you take this man to be thy lawful wedded husband subject to the provisions in section 8 of the addendum attached herewith?”</p> <p><strong>Don’t say:</strong> “My client does.”</p>","internalOctopusCode":"10978450","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-11-16T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2406878","internalContentCode":"458381068","internalRevision":"86","publication":"The Guardian","trailText":"Prenups are growing in popularity, as parents worry that their contribution to a child’s house deposit will be half-inched by a wayward partner","allowUgc":"false","headline":"Why your in-laws want you to sign a prenuptial agreement\r\n","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","commentable":"true","firstPublicationDate":"2015-11-15T18:00:09Z","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/75